    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogy. To explain it properly, a p-value of 0.04 indicates that the probability of observing the results (or more extreme results) by chance is 4%. In other words, if the new blood pressure med is no better than a placebo, there's only a 4% chance of obtaining the observed results or more extreme results.\n\nIn terms of statistical significance, a p-value of 0.04 is considered statistically significant. This means that the results are unlikely to be due to chance, and it's reasonable to conclude that the new med has a significant effect on blood pressure.\n\nHowever, it's essential to remember that statistical significance doesn't necessarily imply clinical significance. A p-value of 0.04 might indicate that the results are statistically significant, but it doesn't necessarily mean that the treatment effect is large enough to be clinically meaningful. To determine this, researchers would also consider the effect size and other factors, such as the magnitude of the treatment effect and its practical significance.",
      "source": "target",
