    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok thats clearer thanks. so if the p-value was like 0.06 instead of 0.04, would that mean the study basically failed? and how do researchers decide where that cutoff line actually is?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A p-value of 0.06 would indicate that the results are not statistically significant, meaning that the probability of observing the results (or more extreme results) by chance is 6%. In this case, it's less likely that the new blood pressure med has a significant effect on blood pressure.\n\nHowever, it doesn't mean the study \"failed.\" Rather, it suggests that the results are not strong enough to support a conclusion that the med is effective. The study might still be worth continuing, as the results might be close to being statistically significant, or the researchers might want to explore other aspects of the study.\n\nAs for the cutoff line, researchers typically use a p-value of 0.05 as the standard threshold for statistical significance. This is because:\n\n1. The probability of observing a false positive (i.e., a result that appears statistically significant when it's not) is 5% or less, which is considered a reasonable risk.\n2. The p-value distribution is typically skewed, with most p-values clustering around 0.05, making it easier to detect statistically significant results.\n\nHowever, some researchers argue that a p-value of 0.05 is too arbitrary and that the true cutoff line might be higher or lower,",
      "source": "target",
